    <script>
        // Article data for modal content - MUST be defined before functions
        const articleData = {
            1: {
                title: "NDA for Confidential Business Projects – Secure Sensitive Data",
                content: `<p class="mb-4">Whether you're in construction, technology, or any other industry, protecting sensitive business information is essential. It helps ensure that your company's competitive edge and intellectual property remain secure. A well-drafted Non-Disclosure Agreement (NDA) establishes legal boundaries for how confidential information can be used and shared, preventing unauthorized disclosure to competitors or the public.</p>
                <p class="mb-4">In the construction industry, NDAs are particularly important when sharing project plans, proprietary methods, client lists, or financial information with subcontractors, suppliers, or potential partners. A comprehensive NDA should clearly define what constitutes confidential information, the duration of the agreement, and the consequences of breach.</p>
                <p class="mb-4">Key elements of an effective construction NDA include: identification of parties, definition of confidential information, exclusions from confidentiality, obligations of receiving party, time period, and jurisdiction for dispute resolution. Both parties should have the agreement reviewed by legal counsel before signing.</p>
                <p>Remember that NDAs are just one part of a comprehensive information protection strategy. Combine them with employee training, secure document management systems, and cybersecurity measures for maximum protection of your sensitive business data.</p>`
            },
            2: {
                title: "Essential Steps to Site Preparation for Construction",
                content: `<p class="mb-4">Before any building can rise from the ground, there's a crucial process that sets the stage for everything that follows—this is called site preparation. This phase involves clearing the land, grading, soil testing, and ensuring proper drainage. Proper site preparation prevents future structural issues, reduces construction delays, and ensures compliance with local building codes and environmental regulations.</p>
                <p class="mb-4">The site preparation process typically begins with surveying and marking boundaries, followed by clearing vegetation, debris, and existing structures. Soil testing determines bearing capacity and identifies any contamination or stability issues. Grading establishes proper drainage slopes and creates level building pads.</p>
                <p class="mb-4">Additional steps may include erosion control measures, utility connections, and addressing any environmental concerns such as protected habitats or wetlands. Professional site preparation requires coordination between surveyors, geotechnical engineers, and excavation contractors.</p>
                <p>Investing in thorough site preparation saves significant time and money by preventing problems during construction. Issues discovered after building begins are much more expensive and difficult to correct than those addressed during preparation.</p>`
            },
            3: {
                title: "Tier 1 Construction Companies in Sydney – Everything You Need to Know",
                content: `<p class="mb-4">The construction industry is vital to Sydney's growth, constantly shaping the city's skyline and infrastructure. Tier 1 construction companies are the largest and most experienced firms, handling major projects worth hundreds of millions of dollars. These companies have extensive resources, sophisticated project management systems, and proven track records delivering complex developments including high-rise buildings, hospitals, and transportation infrastructure.</p>
                <p class="mb-4">Major Tier 1 contractors in Sydney include Lendlease, Multiplex, CPB Contractors, John Holland, and Laing O'Rourke. These companies typically self-perform critical elements while managing extensive networks of subcontractors and suppliers. They maintain large workforces, substantial equipment fleets, and in-house design and engineering capabilities.</p>
